results.title: Portland beef carcase competition 1960
results.brief_description: Promotional film highlighting the quality of Victorian beef. Shots of people looking at meat, etc throughout. Includes disturbing footage of beef carcases being hung. Great ‘The End’ title. See Also: 1955 Pig Carcase Competition at Dandenong and 1957 Pig Carcase Competition at Dandenong.

results.title: Story of the Cat
results.creator_credit: Bob Nagel and International Film Bureau
results.brief_description: A well paced tale of a once curious and exciting cat who becomes content, complacent and boring with age. A simple but eloquent statement on the norms of this world.

results.title: Picking grapes
results.creator_credit: Victoria. Dept. of Agriculture and Jack Keane
results.brief_description: Shot close to the Murry river. Predominantly features instructional sequences on how to pick and process grapes. Nice shots featuring contrasting Orange and Green colours in the soil/grapes. Four soundtracks accompany picture; Italian, German, English and Hungarian.

results.title: Phalaris seed retention
results.brief_description:
In order to negate Phelaris crops from losing their ‘top’ before harvesting, crop-dusting is employed.

Features good footage of plane flying over crops and releasing chemicals.

Largely comprises of an interview between a presenter and a scientist.

results.title: Storm boy. - [Edited version]
results.creator_credit: Henri Safran, Matt Carroll, Learning Corporation of America and South Australian Film Corporation
results.brief_description: Edited version of the feature film of the same name produced in 1977. Story of a boy who lives with his widowed father in a comfortable but ramshackle beach house amidst coastal sand dunes in South Australia’s Coorong. He befriends three young pelicans orphaned by hunters who have shot the mother bird. Adapted from the book of the same title by Colin Thiele. Cast includes Peter Cummins, Greg Rowe, David Gulpilil.

results.title: Packing apples for export
results.brief_description:
Film explains how to correctly pack and store apples for export to Enlgand on ships. Features footage of early automated fruit processing technology, as well as women sorting through apples and packing them. Nice shots, also, of people picking apples and placing them in steel buckets. Classic apple-picking imagery with rich reds and greens. Some slow-motion footage of ‘expert’ demonstrating how to wrap an apple before packing. End of film shot at docks with numerous crates being hiosted onto ships. Narration is upbeat and light.

Beautiful illustrated title and end credits featuring text-over-apples.
